<sec>
<st>
Notable articles</st>

<p>

The article in issue number 4, "Architectural software on the cheap" was contributed by Paul Coates, then working in the School of Architecture at Liverpool Poly. In the opinion of the author, this was one of the earliest examples of the serious use of cheap micros for CAD. In those days the conventional wisdom was that you needed big machines and classy graphics hardware. The article illustrated the use of the PET micro and an A3 plotter for generating floor plans, shadow casting and daylight calculation. The work illustrated was funded by a small RIBA (The Royal Institute of British Architects) grant for teaching architecture using computers.</p>
<p>

The article on TCL Pascal in issue 6 was by Anne Scott and John Stout. </p>

